			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Before you read this reply realize that it is not another "I hate SOE" post, I attempted to take the position of devil's advocate.Assume a neutral position on this issue before you read this reply and try to see both sides of the argument before you respond with flames and whatnot.
<br />

<br />
My disagreements:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">"DOMINANCE OF THE RAID CENTRIC MENTALITY and THE RISE OF THE UBERGUILD"</span>
<br />
The majority of us are interested in making our characters powerful. Killing stronger mobs yields better items, so guilds of people who play multiple hours a night began to excel, and uber guilds were born. 
<br />
The article suggests that it sucks because things are no longer centered around quests and the gap between casual and uber players is huge, etc. If quests still were the dominant focus, who would excel, keeping the gap between uber guilds and casual players as wide as it is now? That's right, those of us who play 6+ hours a night, the uber guilds.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">"THE DEATH OF EPIC STORY TELLING AND THE RISE OF THE WAYFARERS"</span>
<br />
The majority of us don't give a shit about story, we care about our EQ friends and character progression (phat lewts and AAs), not much else. Story was nice when we first started. When Velious came out, sure, the dragons and giants thing was neat at first but after a few weeks the uber players would farm loots from all three places and the regular people would switch factions whenever they needed something from a different faction. Perhaps I am the only one who remembers that many people found the faction thing a nuisance? Killing billions of giants so I could do the prayer shawls was a major pain in the ass. 
<br />
People kill the deity of their character all the time, and we care about story? Give me a break.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">"IGNORING THE PLAYERBASE"</span>
<br />
"For years the EQ playerbase has been posting on the problems of EQ but their cries have fallen on deaf ears."
<br />
Yup, even if 1% of suggestions made by players have been implemented, it's still pretty awesome considering how many suggestions are made. 
<br />
As for the Fan Faire, how would you like it if you were a dev there and the 50th person in two hours came up and started bitching to you about their class and overall class balance? You would want to punch them in the face.
<br />
I thought it was pretty funny that the author linked a "How to do it right" article that was written by two SOE employees. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">"WHAT HAPPENED TO GAMEMASTERS, QUESTS, EVENTS, and the BOTB?"</span> 
<br />
What happened to being a newbie?
<br />
Now that we're all grown up, level 65 with loads of AAs and l33t gear, getting a bottle of milk for a lost GM halfling lady in the middle of Misty Thicket is a waste of time for most people. Sure, some would do it for the nostalgia, then rush off to clear Plane of Time with their buddies.
<br />
GMs are players who joined the Guide system. SOE can not controlthe quantity or quality of the people who apply for the Guide system. It is our own fault that there are hardly any GMs on anymore.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">"PROFITS BEFORE INTEGRITY OF THE GAME"</span>
<br />
This entire category was mere speculation by the author, <span style="font-weight: bold">"SOE now has just a handful of in-house staffers and GM's compared to the numbers they used to have."</span> is just one example. Maybe you're right, perhaps there used to be 100 staffers and 300 "game masters", but there's no reason to refute the numbers SOE gives us about their customer service personnel.
<br />

<br />
Another quote from this section I liked: <span style="font-weight: bold">"Most of the problems with EQ can be attributed to lack of funding for proper testing of expansions that end up released unfinished and full of bugs. It’s also common knowledge that there are only a few actual employees left working on EQ live."</span> We the players just KNOW that nobody works on EQ, and we KNOW that the cause is lack of funding and testing. We have no hard info to back any of these claims up, other than we feel like less work is being done on the game. No hard numbers. 
<br />

<br />
Everquest was meant to make money, and SOE is milking it for all they can. This is how computer games are. Get over it.
<br />

<br />
Perhaps people like the author of this article weren't around when Verant still owned the game. Everyone HATED Verant, the same as it is for SOE today. Nothing will "fix" Everquest, and nothing will "make it fun again" after you've been playing the game for years. 
<br />

<br />
Take this last thought away with you: what makes the game fun for you today? It seems most people want the feeling of what this game used to be. That is not possible. Grouping in Lower Guk and surviving your first train is a feeling that will never be reproduced. Take the game for what it is or quit.
<br />

<br />

<br />
*EDIT*
<br />
Didn't notice Mudspoon's post before I wrote this, but he nailed just about everything on the head. I have one person who somewhat agrees with me, amazing.</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Kelvid Rubblemaker on Tue Jun 01, 2004 11:48 pm; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
