			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Kelvid Rubblemaker wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Nothing will "fix" Everquest, and nothing will "make it fun again" after you've been playing the game for years.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I don't buy that... not one bit.
<br />

<br />
As with all online product it is the CONTENT that provides the entertainment. What SOE has failed to deliver is a balanced delivery of updated content to address the changing demographics of the EQ world.
<br />

<br />
Median levels of players used to be 20... now its more like 40-50. (Numbers pulled out of the air but the premise is sound) Instead of changing content to reflect this they continue to bolt on expansion after expansion with content that is near impossible for 80% of the player base to visit. This kills zones leaving vast areas of the EQ world dead as they are redundent.
<br />

<br />
What is left? LDON... BoT... HoHo... any more? Looks fairly grim for anyone stuck in the middle of being 65 and the so-called Uber guilds.
<br />

<br />
Instead SoE could invest time and energy in balancing the zones to reflect the current needs of the player base.
<br />

<br />
This means putting into old content:
<br />
      More productive and worthwhile tradeskills.
<br />
      Different and more compatable mobs to fight of a level that delivers real exp and loot gains. (Not raids but for groups!)
<br />
      Reintroduce factions as intergral in quests etc. The best quest in the game Coldain Shawl should be a model of how quests should be in EQ.
<br />

<br />

<br />
The aboave would greatly expand the world for those "stuck in the middle" by providing us CONTENT in which to continue coughing up our monthly fees.
<br />

<br />
Its the content that is the issue. SoE COULD give us new fun content that could thrill us just like that first train... all it would take is a little bit of creativity.
<br />

<br />
