			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I agree with your analysis completely.  (But then, I'm not in the "raiding" cliques.  I suppose they might be inclined to offer a different perspective.)
<br />

<br />
Nonetheless, regarding these proposed solutions...  If I might inject a little unpleasant/harsh reality:
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Before you release any more expansions fix the bugs first. Make EQ stable before you add one more iota of content.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I'd love to see that too.  But SoE would be out of business within a year.
<br />

<br />
You might read up on the story of <a href="http://www.catb.org/~esr/jargon/html/M/Mars.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Mars</a> from the Jargon file.
<br />

<br />
Specifically:  <span style="font-style: italic">...the company allowed itself to be sidetracked by a bout of perfectionism into continually improving the design,..</span>
<br />

<br />
SoE is like a shark.  If they stop swimming, they'll drown.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Start using the profits of EQ to hire more Devs, Quality Assurance and Gamemasters. The poor quality and instability of EQ is directly proportional to how much money has been spent on staffing.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Just how much profit are they making?  I started running a few numbers a while back.  Just back of the envelope stuff, really.  Trying to make a few guesses.
<br />

<br />
There's bandwidth.  Hardware (which continually fails and needs upgrading/replacing).  Software support.  Manpower.  Gotta man those server rooms.  Backups.  Software licenses.  (What is their backend database?)  Electricity.  Heat.  Air Conditioning.  Etc.
<br />

<br />
It all adds up pretty fast.  Granted, SoE is pulling in a god awful fortune.
<br />
($13 a month TIMES 12 months TIMES 400,000 accounts EQUALS 62.4 million a year.)
<br />

<br />
On the other hand, each expansion has to be costing them around 5-10 million a pop.  (Just for the developers, artists, hardware, and associated personnel costs.)  Perhaps as high as 20 million...
<br />

<br />
Having 1 person available 24x7 means employing 5.  (No, you can't really work them 168 hours per week.  At least, not for very long.)
<br />

<br />
At a salary of 30k, that would mean 150k total.  But wait, there's benefits.  Social-Security taxes.  Holiday pay.  Vacation time.  Etc.  That ONE 24x7 person can easily run over a quarter of a million annually.  10 people, available 24x7, runs a couple of million.
<br />

<br />
How many servers are there again?
<br />

<br />
It adds up.  A few million here.  A few million there.  Sooner or later, we're going to start talking about some real money...
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I submit to you the problem with EQ is SOE. All of the major problems of EQ find their genesis in SOE and in their subsequent mismanagement. How then did the most successful online game in history go so wrong?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I'm willing to bet that SoE's management staff contains some fairly bright people.  They wouldn't have gotten so far otherwise.
<br />

<br />
Unfortunately, their business objectives conflict with my consumer objectives.
<br />

<br />
What did the DX9 rollout do to improve my playing experience?  Or yours?  But I bet SoE will benefit from it.  Be it by using the same engine in EQ2, or perhaps just from the knowledge and experience gained.
<br />

<br />

<br />
The same is true for a lot of things.  The challenge is trying to second guess SoE's motives.  Where they're trying to position the company for the future.
<br />

<br />
Pity for them that I won't be buying EQ2.  SoE's poor customer experience has really soured me on all their products.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Suggestions for improving things:</span>
<br />

<br />
I would like to reiterate my previous ideas:
<br />

<br />
Given the limitations involved upon SoE's resources, perhaps SoE should consider using their personnel resources as <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="font-style: italic">Force Multipliers</span></span> rather than frontline worker-drones.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">I've previously suggested open-sourcing the client.</span>  (For some arbitrary non-standard proprietary definition of open-source.)
<br />

<br />
Hey, anyone who wants to cheat already has the tools to do so.  So lets level the playing field.  Shift critical functionality from the client back to the server, eliminating the cheats.  Sure, its a bit of work on SoEs part.  But the results in client stability and supported hardware will more than make up for it.  Hell, the extra income from Mac/Linux markets alone would cover the expenses.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Allow users a mechanism by which they can petition for changes, seek support from their peers, and check when the changes will go live.</span>
<br />

<br />
The current system of "Don't like it - LEAVE" just plain sucks.  People LEAVE.
<br />

<br />
So provide a mechanism whereby, if everyone complains, things get changed.  And you know they are being changed.  (Not this "We are checking into all options - please keep paying us" nonsense.)
<br />

<br />
Perhaps more to the point, a mechanism where you can see for yourself that, even though you think KEI should be available everywhere, everyone else disagrees with you.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Right now, the bboards are censured.  Even here on the tower, sad to say.  (Look for locked threads.)  That doesn't really give a fellow the feeling of being able to voice his or her problems.  It's more like "lets sweep it all under the rug, and pretend it doesn't really exist".
<br />

<br />
Enough of that.  The only option it gives folks is to LEAVE.
<br />

<br />
Lets get the problems out in the open.
<br />

<br />
And while we're at it, rather than censuring people with unpopular viewpoints, how about providing a mechanism whereby the players can grade other players comments.  Something like the slashdot comment rating system.  Let the players decide what's important.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">One last thought:  Let the players create their own zones.</span>
<br />

<br />
Yeah, you'll get a few thousand orc-pawn-fest-2004 zones.  But you'll also get a few darn good ones.  SoE could harvest the cream of the crop.  (Just look at some of those XML interfaces that have been created, and imagine what else folks could do.)
<br />

<br />
-Rusty.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
